'''Solid light''' is a hypothetical material, made of [[light]] in a [[solid|solidified state]]. Theoretically, it is possible to make such a material,<ref name="ScienceDaily">[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/05/070506160623.htm "Could Light Behave As A Solid? A New Theory"], ''ScienceDaily'', University of Melbourne, 7 May 2007. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref><ref name="Journals">Raftery, J.; Sadri, D.; Schmidt, S.; Türeci, H. E.; Houck, A. A. [http://journals.aps.org/prx/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevX.4.031043 "Observation of a Dissipation-Induced Classical to Quantum Transition"], ''API Physics'', Phys. Rev. X 4, 031043. Published on 8 September 2014. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref> and there are claims this material was already made,<ref name="Dailymail">Zolfagharifard, Ellie.[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2433175/Have-scientists-accidentally-created-lightsaber-New-form-matter-discovered-seen-science-fiction.html "Have scientists accidentally created a lightsaber? New form of matter discovered that has only ever been used in science-fiction"], ''[[Daily Mail]]'', 26 September 2013. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref><ref name="huffington">Freeman, David.[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/16/solid-light-created_n_5824268.html "Scientists Say They've Created A Freaky New Form Of Light"], ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', 16 September 2014. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref> including claims from [[MIT]] and [[Harvard]].<ref>Reuell, Peter. [http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2013/09/seeing-light-in-a-new-way "Seeing light in a new way"], ''Harvard Gazette'', 27 September 2013. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/science/2013/09/29/mit-harvard-scientists-accidentally-create-real-life-lightsaber.html "MIT, Harvard scientists accidentally create real-life lightsaber"]''Fox News'', 29 September 2013. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref>
== Theory == In theory, [[photon]]s, the particles that make light, could be attracted in a [[nonlinear system|nonlinear]] medium. In test, a [[laser]] beam fired into an extremely cold [[cloud]] of [[rubidium]] slowed down the photons and made them act as a single entity.<ref>Firstenberg, Ofer; Peyronel, Thibault; Liang, Qi-Yu; Gorshkov, Alexey V.; Lukin, Mikhail D.; Vuletić, Vladan. [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v502/n7469/full/nature12512.html "Attractive photons in a quantum nonlinear medium"], ''[[Nature (magazine)|Nature]]'', 25 September 2013. Retrieved on January 30 2016.</ref><ref>Emspak, Jesse. [http://news.discovery.com/tech/gear-and-gadgets/solid-light-light-sabers-made-photons-130927.htm "'Solid Light' Made from Photons"], ''[[Discovery News]]'', 27 September 2013. Retrieved on 30 January 2016.</ref>
== Fiction == Solid light appears in many [[video game franchises]], including ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'', ''[[Portal (video game series)|Portal]]'', ''[[Mass Effect (series)|Mass Effect]]'' and ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]''. It is also portrayed in ''The Lightbringer'' series by fantasy author [[Brent Weeks]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} It also appears in Dr. Strange. {{cn|date=August 2018}} The Gems, a fictional [[alien race]] featured in ''[[Steven Universe]]'', are [[Gemstone|gemstones]] that project physical bodies made of solid light.
