{{unreferenced|date=November 2016}} [[File:Contacting surfaces.jpg|thumb|Contacting surfaces with applied normal and tangential forces]]
{{expert needed|1=Physics|reason=There appear to be lots of potential sources for this, but none that cover the basics mentioned in this article. It also seems like there should be better categories|date=November 2016}}
'''Normal contact stiffness''' is a physical quantity related to the generalized force displacement behavior of [[Surface roughness|rough surface]]s in contact with a [[rigid body]] or a second similar rough surface.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} As two solid bodies of the same material approach one another, they transition from conditions of non-contact to homogeneous bulk type behaviour. The varying values of stiffness and true contact area that is exhibited at an interface during this transition is dependent on conditions of applied pressure and is of notable importance for the study of systems involving the physical interactions of multiple bodies including [[granular matter]], [[electrode]] contacts, and [[thermal contact]]s, where the interface-localized structures govern overall system performance.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
==Surface structure== The role of [[surface structure]] in normal contact mechanics, in terms of stiffness and true contact area is a frequently studied topic.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} Parameters of roughness, [[fractal dimension]] and [[Asperity (materials science)|asperity geometry]] are often discussed{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} with reference to their significance on contact mechanics of surfaces.
[[Category:Surfaces]] [[Category:Physics]] [[Category:Mechanics]] [[Category:Friction]] [[Category:Classical mechanics]] [[Category:Force]]

A '''Resistive plate chamber''' (RPC) is a [[particle detector]] widely used in [[high energy physics]]. They are used for detecting [[muon]]s in most of the modern experiments including [[ATLAS experiment|ATLAS]], [[Compact Muon Solenoid|CMS]], and [[BES III]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ATLAS Detector|url=https://atlas.cern/discover/detector/muon-spectrometer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CMS Detector|url=https://cms.cern/detector/detecting-muons}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Physics at BES-III|journal=International Journal of Modern Physics A|volume=A24|issue=1|arxiv=0809.1869|bibcode=2008arXiv0809.1869A|last1=Asner|first1=D. M|last2=Barnes|first2=T|last3=Bian|first3=J. M|last4=Bigi|first4=I. I|last5=Brambilla|first5=N|last6=Boyko|first6=I. R|last7=Bytev|first7=V|last8=Chao|first8=K. T|last9=Charles|first9=J|last10=Chen|first10=H. X|last11=Chen|first11=J. C|last12=Chen|first12=Y|last13=Chen|first13=Y. Q|last14=Cheng|first14=H. Y|last15=Dedovich|first15=D|last16=Descotes-Genon|first16=S|last17=Fu|first17=C. D|last18=Tormo|first18=X. Garcia i|last19=Gao|first19=Y. -N|last20=He|first20=K. L|last21=He|first21=Z. G|last22=Hu|first22=J. F|last23=Hu|first23=H. M|last24=Huang|first24=B|last25=Jia|first25=Y|last26=Jin|first26=H. -Y|last27=Jin|first27=S|last28=Kuang|first28=Y. P|last29=Lacker|first29=H|last30=Li|first30=H. B|displayauthors=29|year=2008}}</ref>
