{{Cat main|Physical quantity}}
{{Commons category}}

This [[Wikipedia:Category|category]] identifies [[physical quantity|physical quantities]] which are necessary defined quantities, measured, manipulated, generally used by [[physicist]]s, [[engineer]]s, [[chemist]]s, etc.

[[Category:Physics]]
[[Category:Quantity]]

A '''perpendicular paramagnetic bond''' is a type of chemical bond (in contrast to [[Covalent bond|covalent]] or [[Ionic bonding|ionic]] bonds) that does not exist under normal, atmospheric conditions.<ref name=lange/> Such a phenomenon was first hypothesized through simulation to exist in the atmospheres of [[white dwarf]] stars<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2012-07-chemists-molecular-bond-white-dwarf.html|title=Chemists discover new type of molecular bond near white dwarf stars|website=phys.org|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> whose magnetic fields, on the order of 10<sup>5</sup> [[Tesla (unit)|teslas]],<ref name=lange>{{cite journal |last1=Lange |first1=K. K. |last2=Tellgren |first2=E. I. |last3=Hoffmann |first3=M. R. |last4=Helgaker |first4=T. |title=A Paramagnetic Bonding Mechanism for Diatomics in Strong Magnetic Fields |journal=Science |date=19 July 2012 |volume=337 |issue=6092 |pages=327–331 |doi=10.1126/science.1219703|pmid=22822146}}</ref> allow such interactions to exist. Normally, at such intense temperatures as those near a white dwarf, more common molecular bonds cannot form and existing ones decompose.<ref name=":0" />
